{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/language-wars-7d16ebdba15e", "time": 1683009713.742573, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/language-wars-7d16ebdba15e/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Language wars. Choosing a language for Data Science \u2014\u2026 | by Dimitris Panagopoulos | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Language wars", "description": "Being an enthusiastic reader of Towards Data Science for a few time I couldn\u2019t help but notice the debate on the best language for Data Science. Examples are: This is just a short post with some of\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "http://danifold.net/mapper/introduction.html", "anchor_text": "mapper", "paragraph_index": 5}], "all_paragraphs": ["Being an enthusiastic reader of Towards Data Science for a few time I couldn\u2019t help but notice the debate on the best language for Data Science. Examples are:", "This is just a short post with some of my thoughts on the subject. Unfortunately, I am not familiar with Julia, hence it is mostly on using R and/or Python.", "In my opinion, one should use the language that best fits one needs. Having tried to use TensorFlow in R was a nightmare. I know that it can be done and maybe it had to do with my inexperience but installation is complex. Furthermore, documentation and sources in Python are light-years away compared to that in R. As for PyTorch, I am not aware of ways of integrating it with R. If you want to develop deep learning solutions then choose Python over R.", "Also, as a Greek native speaker, I have tried R for natural language processing in greek corpora. It simply cannot be done. Problems range from encoding errors to non-existent support in popular packages. On the other hand, several NLP libraries support Greek and if not, there is a way to add support by yourself. The same applies to other languages. If you have a non-english NLP language, choose Python over R.", "On the other hand, R and CRAN make installing libraries a straight forward process. It is very unusual to have broken dependencies and conflicting versions/packages. Here Python is left far behind. Also, I have encountered cases where I could install R packages behind a corporate firewall but not Python packages even though according to IT none of the involved repositories were blocked. If you want to easily set up and running (more especially behind a firewall) choose R over Python.", "Finally, there are specific use cases where one library is available to only one language. If that is the case then the selection is easy. For example, a couple of years ago only Python had packages for the mapper algorithm from topological data analysis.", "Sometimes a data scientist is not given a choice. If you are hired and joined a team that uses R then you are going to have to use R. If you start a project and only Python is available, then you are going to use Python. This might sound obvious but it is something that you take into account when applying for a position or when you are considering your career path. If you want to join a company/team that uses R, then you should know how to use it. Being a Python expert is a plus but not sufficient!", "In my opinion, what makes a data scientist special is good knowledge of the fundamental workings of tools. One should know the basic theory of the most common algorithms. Furthermore, he should the advantages and disadvantages and when to choose one over the other. And ideally, he should have real-life experience using them. So my advice is to know your theory, select a project, select a language, and get your hands dirty.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F7d16ebdba15e&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/si